data.content:
Yes — use **tuples** to get type safety and avoid `object[]` boxing:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Why this is better:**
- **Type-safe** — compile-time errors instead of runtime casts
- **Named fields** — self-documenting test data
- **No boxing** — `bool` stays a value type

> Requires **MSTest 3.8+**, which added tuple support for `[DynamicData]`. If you're on an older version, `[DataRow]` is the simplest alternative for constant values like these:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```
